    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w35109</id>
    <title>Early Childcare Attendance and Cognitive skills in Adolescence</title>
    <updated>2026-04-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Ingvild Almås, Nina Drange, Costas Meghir &amp; Henrik D. Zachrisson</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper examines the impact of early childcare on academic achievement for children in grade 5 and grade 9, based on a 2003 policy expansion that created quasi-random variation in slot availability for children aged 1–2. Starting childcare one year earlier increases math scores by 9.7% of a standard deviation (SD) in grade 9. Children whose mothers do not hold a high school diploma benefit by a significant 28% of a SD at grade 9, reducing the math achievement gap from children of higher-educated mothers by about one third. We also present evidence of strong improvements for children of immigrants.</content>
